An Act relating to the Department of Mental Health
and Substance Abuse Services; directing the
Department designate an individual to address the
Department's consent decree; providing qualifications
for the designee; establishing the authority of the
designee; implementing the responsibilities of the
designee; providing for codification; and declaring
an emergency.
SUBJECT: Department of Mental Health and Substance Abuse Services
BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 2-112 of Title 43A, unless there
is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
A. The Department of Mental Health and Substance Abuse Services
shall designate an individual to specifically implement the
requirements of the consent decree resulting from Briggs et al v.
Friesen et al, Case No. 23-CV-00081 (N.D. Okla. Mar. 10, 2025).
B. The designee shall have the requisite training, knowledge,
and credentials to advise the Department in meeting the requirements
of the consent decree. The designee shall have at a minimum the
following requirements:
1. Hold a degree of M.D., D.O., Ph.D., or a Psy.D.;
2. A specialty certification in Forensic Psychiatry or Forensic
Psychology;

3. A specific knowledge of the Oklahoma criminal justice and
competency system; and
4. Experience performing competency evaluations and competency
restoration within the last five (5) years.
C. The designee shall:
1. Have the authority to design and manage the section or
division of Forensic Services at the Department;
2. Report only to the Commissioner of Mental Health and
Substance Abuse Services but shall also answer as requested to the
Oklahoma Legislature;
3. Have hiring and firing authority, working in coordination
with the Human Resources Office at the Department;
4. Have ultimate supervisory authority over all current and
future forensic staff including treatment providers and evaluators;
5. Be responsible for all policies, credentialing, training,
and education of all forensic evaluators utilized by the Department;
6. Be responsible for all quality and professional standards
regarding forensic evaluations performed by the Department;
7. Be responsible for all communication with jails and courts
regarding defendants within the forensic system;
8. Have responsibility for all forensic-related legislation
that derives from the Department and shall work with the staff of
the Speaker of the Oklahoma House of Representatives and the
President Pro Tempore of the Oklahoma State Senate in designing and
pursuing such legislation;
9. Work and collaborate with the federally approved monitors
assigned by the consent decree in Briggs et al v. Friesen et al,
Case No. 23-CV-00081 (N.D. Okla. Mar. 10, 2025), and shall be
allowed to meet outside of the presence of any other Department
employee or contracted legal firm, including the Department's
general counsel;
